This question requires multiple uses of the chain rule.

\begin{align*}\displaystyle f(x) = \ln(1 + \ln(1 + \ln(1 + x)))\end{align*} Recognizing that
the inner function is $u = h(x) = 1 + \ln(1 + \ln(1 + x))$ and the outer
function is $g(u) = \ln(u)$, we apply the chain rule and get

\begin{align*}
f'(x) &= g'(h(x))\cdot h'(x) \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + \ln(1 + \ln(1 + x))}\cdot h'(x).\end{align*} Now we need to use the chain rule again to evaluate
$h'(x)$. The function $h(x)$ has inner function
$v = k(x) = 1 + \ln(1 + x)$ and outer function $j(v) = 1 + \ln(v)$.
Thus, $h'(x)$ is given by

\begin{align*}
h'(x) &= j'(k(x))\cdot k'(x)\\
&= \frac{1}{1 + \ln(1 + x)}\cdot k'(x) \\
&= \frac{1}{1 + \ln(1 + x)}\cdot \frac{1}{1 + x}\end{align*} Thus putting the pieces together, we write the expression
for the derivative of $f$:

\begin{align*}{\color{blue}f'(x) = \frac{1}{1 + \ln(1 + \ln(1 + x))}\cdot\frac{1}{1 + \ln(1 + x)}\cdot\frac{1}{1 + x}
}.\end{align*}
